 Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $MB_{p}(X)$
\end_inset

 is the set of all variables which given them 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is independent of all other variables in the graph, we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $ne(X)\subset MB_{p}(X)$
\end_inset

 in any case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But since we also know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 is a P-map of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 we also know that all independencies that are present is 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 are also present in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 In addition we also know that 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is positive, and that means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}(p)=\mathcal{I}(\mathcal{H})=\mathcal{I}_{local}(\mathcal{H})$
\end_inset

 and This tells us that no node that is outside of 
\begin_inset Formula $ne(X)$
\end_inset

 could be in 
\begin_inset Formula $MB_{p}(X)$
\end_inset

, since the only independencies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 has are modeled by the neighbors, and that means that 
\begin_inset Formula $ne(X)\supset MB_{p}(X)$
\end_inset

 which all together brings us to 
\begin_inset Formula $ne(X)=MB_{p}(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
